The “AI Agent Knowledge Capture and Scaling” proposal shows strong potential, but the current model appears to focus mainly on accelerated productivity (~£5.85m saving) without fully accounting for:
• ongoing AI/token consumption costs
• scaling and capacity limitations
• operational/compliance costs and risks in a regulated environment
For the “Software Ingestion Modernisation” proposal, direct cost savings are harder to attribute to a single team because this is a foundational enterprise platform capability.
The value comes from enabling and accelerating cost savings across development teams by:
• accelerating software ingestion onboarding into JPMC
• reducing manual engineering effort and delivery friction
• improving security, governance, and standardisation
• reducing operational risk
• enabling faster delivery and time-to-market across many teams
This is similar to platforms like Stylus, where the platform itself is not the end cost-saving outcome, but the enterprise enabler that allows downstream teams to deliver faster, more securely, and more efficiently at scale.
